</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,1513,2006]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,494,1657,1682]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
Notes on 
<typeStatus box="[308,359,1657,1682]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">type</typeStatus>
specimens.
</emphasis>
The male 
<typeStatus box="[612,710,1657,1682]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">holotype</typeStatus>
and the female 
<typeStatus box="[886,983,1658,1682]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">paratype</typeStatus>
are attached to the same pin. There is no question as to which of the specimens should be regarded as 
<typeStatus box="[851,952,1693,1718]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">holotype</typeStatus>
, because Curran (
<number box="[1156,1214,1694,1718]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="1930.0">1930</number>
) clearly designated the male as such. Unfortunately, the abdomen of the male is missing. Nonetheless, its genitalia are conserved in a microvial attached to the pin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,1513,2006]" box="[199,754,1801,1826]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
